Two days ago on Sunday. We were able to get seats right away in back yard. I originally called and asked of there were reservations needed. A She stated no. So that was a plus. Everything is booked and waiting time is long due to covid. Very pretty backyard. But that was the highlight of the evening. We were told by host there is a 90 min limited. There was no music. The menu was limited to maybe 7 items. There are no full meals. We kept asking waiter to explain what full meals were there, such as rice, chicken, a side etc. He stated there was a full meal pointed it out in the menu. It came, it was a green pepper stuffed with chewy cheese. Not fulfilling. I ended up getting 2 small tacos, soggy tacos with lots of shredded chicken sprinkled with Queso Fresco cheese and cilantro. I've never seen such a boring, tasteless and expensive Taco $12.  Needless to say, we were still hungry. Waiter kept pushing that everyone was purchasing bits here and there off the menu. We wanted a full meal. You know the kind you go to a restaurant when it's 2 o'clock in the day and you haven't eaten anything for the day and now you're hungry for a full meal not appetizers. We ended having to buy another meal at the nearby shake shack🤦🏽‍♀️

I went there on Saturday and was impressed by their efforts to keep us safe from Covid: all staff wearing masks correctly and consistently, appropriately physically-distanced tables, sanitizing the menus in between use, and hand sanitizer available everywhere. 👍🏽👍🏽  I had the pepino margarita with the ceviche and the quesadillas. Everything was excellent - delicious and fresh. The service was great. The ambiance in the garden patio was perfect. Highly recommend!

This is a must if you enjoy well put together food dishes and well formulated cocktails. Shannon is an amazing bartender. She knows her Mezcal! Order the drink with watermelon and absinthe. As for the food- it is outstanding. The chef knows what he is doing. Do yourself a favor: order the guac and chips!! Just DO IT :) Then I received a delicious avocado-micro green type salad...it was to die for. Hey Gran Electrica- PUT THIS SALAD ON YOUR MENU! The cherry tomatoes were insanely fresh and the dressing needs to be in a bottle and sold. haha Then I got this dish with head on prawns, calamari and mussels in a dark, earthy, somewhat spicy broth. Perfect for the white rice they provide to soak up the broth. Taco's are also worth it and their brunch menu is also very tasty. Sit in the backyard if you can- it's like a tropical oasis.

Seriously the BEST random restaurant that we found in Brooklyn after walking over the Brooklyn Bridge! It’s a regional Mexican flare plus mescal & tequila cocktails! I recommend you trying the Margarita De Toronja Picante!!! It’s an infused habanero margarita that you will DIE FOR! The dishes they have there are just as good as the drinks! OH and try the platanos!! They are a member of the banana family. They are much smaller than a typical banana, have a starchy sweet flavor to them, they are cooked and crispy when swerved with crème. If you have never had them before I recommend trying them for sure. They are different and delicious! *The atmosphere here is AMAZING! There is a sexy dim lighted bar right when you walk in and a romantic outdoor back patio area with lots of greenery in the back. The staff is outgoing, polite and just genuinely nice. The bartenders are over the top and basically put on a show for you with their skill of flipping and shaking drinks while you sit there and enjoy your time. One of my favorite spots that we stopped at while I was in NYC for Labor Day weekend.

Pumped up after reading fabulous reviews of Gran Electrica, and hoping to see the raved about mole or crab tostadas, my family ventured over excitedly one Sunday evening. We currently live in Pittsburgh, where amazing restaurants now abound (as in Brooklyn), but we return to Brooklyn often, and travel elsewhere frequently, as well. First, I must say the outside garden, cocktails and service was great. While vibe outside was fun, the pumping D.J. music might be best suited to twenty-somethings. The food was decent, cooked well, but not as exciting as I'd hoped -- lacked the pizazz that'd bring us back to spend more money. The dishes were all tiny, i.e. $11 guac and chips yielded a tiny bowl barely big enough for two, let alone our table of four, and my ceviche was in a tiny champagne glass.  Although, I'd say the tacos were a decent amount for the price. The menu didn't look as exciting as we'd hoped, offering nothing we read about in reviews, and the seasoning left something to be desired. My ceviche was essentially fish with bits of citrus, and at the bottom I found a few barely noticeable chunks of avocado and onion. The carnitas tacos were good, but pretty much just meat again. The Pescado Al Horno with peanuts was good, well cooked fish, but seemed to need a punch. The whole meal seemed to need a punch. (I should mention that my son said the chorizo quesadilla was very tasty.) Perhaps this would be  a good fit if we just wanted good tacos and drinks on a date night. And maybe we stopped by on a bad night, maybe the menu will switch to exciting food again, but there are too many other tasty Mexican options in Brooklyn.
